Project 4 - Write a Data Science Blog Post¶

Introduction¶

This project is part of the Udacity Become a Data Scientist Nanodegree. The task is to take one or more datasets, ask 3-5 questions that you then seek to answer following the CRISP-DM. The questions have to be answered using statistical analysis and if necessary machine learning algorithms. After the analysis the results shall be published in form of a blogpost on a website like Medium.

This notebook is structured roughly similar to the CRISP-DM. In the first few sections I'll be trying to develop a business and data understanding. Next, I'll prepare the data for analysis. And the last part is the actual analysis. Usually in the CRISP-DM, expecially when using machine learning, you divide it into "modelling", "evaluation" and "deployment". In this notebook these steps are somewhat mixed. In trying to analyse a certain part of the data, I've tried to set up the methods and procedures that would allow me to do so. During this process, I've tried different methods and regularly updated the methods or even went back to data-preparation to improve on the analysis. The deployment itself can be seen as the final analysis and the blogpost itself. I've not marked every iteration of this process, as this would make the notebook rather messy, but you can still see some iterations such as further aggregating regions after realising the first aggregation resulted in chaotic graphics for the analysis.

As for the data to analyse I followed the suggestion in the project outline and used the yearly StackOverflow survey, the datasets can be found here: https://insights.stackoverflow.com/survey. The results are also available in the subdirectory of this repository named "Data".

Developing a Business (and Data) Understanding¶

The tricky thing with a project like this is, that you don't start your exploration with a question in mind. You are given the dataset and based on that you have to then find a few questions to ask. Thus, the first step is to get a feeling for the data you are given and understand what information you have to work with. Then you can start to formulate questions and create knowledge. Looking at the CRISP-DM structure, I'll be ping-ponging between Business and Data Understanding in the first few steps in an attempt to develop a business understanding. I might also have to delve into data preparation tasks early on to properly understand the data.

For this project I chose to analyze the results of the yearly Stackoverflow surveys, going back to the year 2011. Let's take a look and get a first impression on the data.

5 rows × 65 columns

The first observation is that there is a large number of columns with the label "Unnamed". No schema is provided with the dataset. One option is to drop the unnamed columns, though they could provide interesting insights. Maybe there is a way to recreate a label of the column based on the answers (samples). Additionally, the other column labels are long questions rather than a short label.

The second observation is that the first row seems to give additional information on the column rather than being the first set of survey answers.

Maybe there is a way to define short labels for all columns based on the question in the current label, the first row and the answers in the other rows.

Time to skip through all the columns and find an appropriate label...

In [5]:
def print_col_info(df, col = 0):
    if CURRENT_COLUMN >= df.shape[1]:
        print('-' * 50)
        print('That was the last column.')
        print('-' * 50)
        return
    print('-' * 50)
    print('Column {} of {}'.format(CURRENT_COLUMN, df.shape[1]))
    print('-' * 50)
    print('Current Label: --------- {}'.format(df.columns[col]))
    print('1st Row: --------------- {}'.format(df.iloc[0,col]))
    print('-' * 50)
    print(df.iloc[:,col].value_counts())
    print('-' * 50)

Business Understanding: Which questions to ask the data?¶

Since this project is part of a data science program and the datasets have been publically available for a while, I'm going to assume most interesting questions have been asked already. Then again it does not seem necessary to ask and answer any "big questions". Even little things can give interesting insights if put into new perspective. Something I am personally very interested in is the difference of the IT communities in different countries. Are German programmers different to American ones? Are British ones different to main land Europe's? Are Europe's programmers different to Asia's? What about the growing IT community in Africa?

  1. There is a difference in age distribution across regions. Is there a similar difference in the age of the Stack Overflow users across the countries? How does the age develop over time?
  2. Work has a very different value across the world. Is there a difference in job satisfaction across the countries? How does the job satisfaction develop over time?
  3. There is a difference in the core industries between the regions. Other programming languages might very well be required. So, is there also a difference in the programming techs/languages used across the countries? How does this develop over time?
  4. So in several years StackOverflow asked about programming as a hobby. Seeing as there is a cultural difference with how much time you spend at work and which hobbies are socially desired - is there a difference in programming as a hobby between the regions?
  5. The economy is quite different across different countries and regions, as is the culture. Is there a difference in company sizes between the regions? Did this change over time?
  1. Are there differences in what people look for in a job across countries? Does this change over time?
  2. Are there differences in how people like to be contacted for a job across countries? Does this change over time?

While the last two questions are also interesting, I'll ignore them for the scope of this project, as I only have a short amount of time to finish. Especially with the data preparation needed for this analysis, I'll be plenty busy. I'll very likely pick up those two questions after the Nanodegree, out of curiousity.

Looks like the age column looks mostly the same throughout the years, with the exception of 2017 (no age column) and 2018 (different scaling).   • Between 25 and 34 years
  • Older than 35 years

This split also shows three major stages in life: before 25 many are still within their training / education, between 25 and 35 many start their career, after 35 most already have quite some experience in their field.

  • Category 1: Students, trainees and job starters (<25)
  • Category 2: Moving up career ladder, gaining experience (25-34)
  • Category 3: Experienced programmers (35+)

Another alternative is to ignore both 2017 and 2018. The three categories make sense though. So, I feel it's fine to group them this way and thus include 2018 in the analysis.

Data Preparation: Let's get busy and clean up that chaos!¶

Now it's time to prepare the data for analysis. While we don't need to form a neural network or a complicated machine learning algorithm to answer our questions, we still need to reorganize the variables, label them properly and shape them in a way that can be used for analysis.

One thing we're going to do a lot is map manifestations of a variable into a few categories. Using dictionaries the normal mapping functions allow you to map a given value onto a new one. That seems impracticle in our case. As we'd have to repeat the category for each manifestation.

Instead, let's use dictionary with the categories as keys and as items have lists with all the possible manifestations that fall under that category. Then let's create a function that maps a given item to such a dictionary.

In [35]:
def map_to_category(item, category_dict, ignore_na=False):
    """Map an item to a category.

    Args:
        item: value to be mapped to a category
        category_dict: dictionary with categories and associated items
        ignore_na: should NaNs be ignored
    
    Returns:
        category for the given item, or 'unassigned' if the item is not assigned to a category
    """
    if ignore_na and item is np.nan:
        return np.nan
    else:
        for category, item_list in category_dict.items():
            if item in item_list:
                return category
    return 'unassigned'

Language Affinities¶

The best way is most likely to create a separate variable for each language, framework or technology. In the dataframes for the years 2011-2015 that has already been done. However, the answers in these years are stored as the name of the language/tech if the person knows or used it and NaN if (s)he doesn't. To make this easier to use for analysis, let's start by mapping the language-strings to 1 and the NaNs to 0. A 1 in this case will mean that a person knows or has worked with a language/tech.

In [52]:
def map_to_one(item, match):
    """Map item to 1 or 0.
    
    Args:
        item: item to be matched; can be a list of items
        match: value to be matched against
        
    Returns:
        1 if item matches or a match is in the given list, 0 otherwise
    """
    new_item = 0
    if type(item) == list and match in item or item == match:
        new_item= 1
        
    return new_item

Discussion:

For 2016 there is a single variable that needs to be split up "Lang_Tech_Used". Multiple answers were allowed for the corresponding question and they were all stored in a single variable in a string format and separated with semicolon + space.

For 2017 and 2018 the question was divided into four separating language, framework, database and platform. They were named HaveWorkedLanguage and LanguageWorkWith respectively. The answers were stored as string representation of a list, the elements of which are separated by a semicolon + space in 2017 and a semicolon (no space) in 2018.

A simple "get_dummies" will not work cause we want to separate the list-strings. We'll have to define a procedure to split them up.

  1. For each sample: Split up the strings and create proper lists
  2. Also, create one list with all the unique elements
  3. Create a new variable in the dataframe for each unique element "Lang_TechUsed*Element"
  4. For each sample: if element is in list, set corresponding variable to 1, else 0

Once again the 1 will mean the person has worked with a tech or language. A 0 could be that the person either did not answer or did not work with the tech or language. Important for the analysis is mostly the 1s however.

# let's create a method to transform the strings to lists
def parse_list(list_string, delimiter, year, ignore_na=False):
    """Converts a list-string for the techs into a proper list. Adds unique techs to the associated dictionary.
    
    Args:
        list_string: list of techs formatted as a string
        delimiter: the delimiter used in the list-string
        year: the year this list-string is taken from
        
    Returns:
        a list representation of the given list-string
    """
    
    if ignore_na and list_string is np.nan:
        return np.nan
    
    tech_list = list_string.split(delimiter)
    
    for tech in tech_list:
        if tech not in unique_techs[year]:
            unique_techs[year].append(tech)
            
    return tech_list

Programming as a hobby¶

As planned we're going to map the values to either 1 for "does program as hobby" and 0 for "does not program as hobby". For the years 2015 and 2016 we'll treat the string "None" as "No", seeing as the other answers are defining a set of time per week you spend on programming as a hobby and the missing values are NaNs. As there are various values for "yes" and only one for "no" in all years, the map_to_one method doesn't work as smoothly. Instead we'll use a "map to 0" function.

In [73]:
def map_to_zero(item, match, ignore_na=False):
    """Map item to 0 or 1.
    
    Args:
        item: item to be matched
        match: value to be matched against
        
    Returns:
        0 if item matches or a match is in the given list, 1 otherwise
    """
    
    if ignore_na and item is np.nan:
        return np.nan
    
    new_item = 1
    if item == match:
        new_item= 0
        
    return new_item

Modelling, Evaluation and Deployment¶

The questions asked do not rely on some kind of machine learning model to be answered, which is not uncommon in data science. Therefore, the modelling and evaluation part is done by a statistical analysis and visualisation.

For the visual analysis each region will receive a specific color, which will be consistent throughout the analysis. The first step is to provide basic information about the amount of participants in each region per year. This will give a better insight into how much significance the given insights hold for the greater total of developers in the region.

In [90]:
def aggregate_regions(df):
    """Aggregates the regions further, adding a row with the total and one for each major part of the world.
    
    Args:
        df: a dataframe with the regions as columns
        
    Returns:
        The given dataframe with 5 additional rows: Total, Europe and Russia, USA and Canada, Asia, Africa and Middle East.
    """
    df['Total'] = df.sum(axis=1)
    df['Europe and Russia'] = df['Germany'] + df['France'] + df['United Kingdom'] + df['Russia'] + df['Europe Other']
    df['USA and Canada'] = df['United States of America'] + df['Canada']
    df['Asia'] = df['Asia Other'] + df['India']
    df['Africa and Middle East'] = df['Africa'] + df['Middle East']
    
    return df

def splitSeriesToArray(series):
    """ Helper function for plotting lines between discrete points even if ticks are skipped (dataless)
    
    Args:
        series: a pandas series
    
    Returns:
        A list with the index of the series and a matrix-representation of the series.
    """
    return [series.index, series.as_matrix()]
In [97]:
def plot_df(df, columns, color_dict=None, title='Untitled', xlabel='Years', ylabel='', yticks=None, linestyle='-'):
    """Plots specific columns of a dataframe
    
    Args:
        df: Dataframe with the data to be plotted
        columns: a list of columns to be plotted
        color_dict: a dictionary describing the color of the given columns; default: None
        title: string; the title of the plot; default: 'Untitled'
        xlabel: string; the X-label of the plot; default: 'Years'
        ylabel: string; the Y-label of the plot; default: ''
        yticks: list; can be used to specify Y-ticks; default: None
        linestyle: string; style of the plotted lines; default: '-'
    """
    fig1 = plt.figure(figsize=(16,10))
    ax1 = fig1.gca()

    for col in columns:
        if color_dict is None:
            ax1.plot(*splitSeriesToArray(df[col].dropna()), label=col, linewidth=1, linestyle=linestyle, marker='o')
        else:
            ax1.plot(*splitSeriesToArray(df[col].dropna()), color=color_dict[col],
                     label=col, linewidth=1, linestyle=linestyle, marker='o')

    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.legend()
    
    if yticks is not None:
        plt.yticks(yticks)
    
    n_xticks = len(plt.xticks()[0])
    if n_xticks > 15:
        plt.xticks(rotation=90)

    ax1.yaxis.grid(True, linestyle='--')
    #plt.grid()

    plt.show()

Okay, now we have regional dataframes. Next up is defining a function that takes a certain variable (label) and the manifestation of that variable we want to look at. It should return a dataframe with regions as columns and years as rows for exactly that variable. Since not all variables are included in all years the function should be able to deal with years where that's the case.

In [104]:
def rearrange_regional_data(col, attr, excluded_years):
    """Create a dataframe for a single manifestation of a variable (counting occurences of that manifestation)
    
    Args:
        col: the variable (column label) to take as basis
        attr: the manifestation of the variable to be analysed
        excluded_years: a list of years excluded from the analysis
        
    Returns:
        Dataframe with a regional comparison over time
    """
    # prep the data 
    data = {year: [] for year in survey_years}
    for year in survey_years:
        for region, r_df in regional_data[year].items():
            if region != 'Other' and year not in excluded_years:
                attribute_count = r_df[col].value_counts().sort_index()
                if attribute_count.shape[0] > 0:
                    data[year].append(attribute_count[attr])
            else:
                data[year].append(0)
    # create a df out of the data
    df = pd.DataFrame(data)
    df.index = regional_data[2018].keys()
    df = df.sort_index()
    df = df.T
    # add a couple extra columns and further aggregate the data
    df = aggregate_regions(df)
    # return the dataframe
    return df

Comparing the absolute values makes little sense as there is a large difference in participants per region. We need relative values instead. However, there is a problem when using relative values as well. My first impulse is to use the total of participants in each year and region to calculate the relative values. Yet, this will skew the data, especially in 2018 where almost 35% of the participants did not answer the question. The question is whether we the data of participants who did not answer the question provide any further insights. As we're not trying to find relations between different variables and just looking at the one variable, counting the number of occurences something happens, I don't believe the missing data points are providing any necessary insights. Instead of using the yearly regional total of participants we can instead form a new one: the yearly regional total of participants who answered the question. As long as we make sure we use this total in all plots for this variable and make this decision clear in our discussion of the observations, this should be fine.

Language Affinities¶

So, for languages we'll need a different approach. Firstly, let's create a dataframe grouping the languages used count in each region for each year. We'll end up with 8 dataframes for each year, the regions as columns, the languages as rows and the count as cells. Of course, we'll once again have to aggregate the regions.

Since for the languages we can't differentiate between "has not answered" and "answered no" let's make the assumption that anyone who knows a language or tech has answered with yes and all others did not answer the question. This means we'll use the total count of participants per region to calculate the relative values. As the language dataframes are different in shape to the participants_per_region dataframe, we'll have to define a function that calculates the relative values and can't just divide the dataframes directly.

Once we have the language dataframes set up we can analyze them. One interesting insight could be getting the top X languages in each region in each year. Maybe we can also define a number of top languages overall and track them for each region over time, similar to how we did it with the other variables before.

The language columns all have the prefix "Lang_TechUsed". It would be nice to only grab the language and ignore the prefix when setting the row labels for our language dataframes.

In [132]:
def parse_lang_label(label):
    """Parses label of the language columns.
    
    Args:
        label: string; column label with the prefix 'Lang_Tech_Used_'
    
    Returns:
        the language part of the label as string
    """
    lang = label.split('_')
    lang = lang[3:]
    lang = ' '.join(lang)
    return lang

# set up a dict to hold all the language dataframes
languages_per_region = {year: {} for year in survey_years}

for year in survey_years:
    year_data = {}
    year_langs = [] # list of unique languages in this year; used for setting the index labels later
    # get the non-language column labels in this year
    cols_to_drop = get_non_lang_columns(year)

    # iterate over the regions
    for region, region_df in regional_data[year].items():
        # drop all non-language columns
        lang_df = region_df.drop(columns=cols_to_drop)
        lang_df[lang_df == 0.0] = np.nan # make sure value_counts only counts the participants that used the language
        year_data[region] = []
        
        # now iterate over all languages of this year
        for col in lang_df.columns:
            # first grab the actual language and drop the unnecessary prefix
            lang = parse_lang_label(col)
            # ignore 'Other' as we want to only look at the main languages
            if lang == 'Other':
                continue
            # add this language to this years languages if it isn't already
            elif lang not in year_langs:
                year_langs.append(lang)
            # add the count of the current language, if the count is 0 add 0
            lang_count = lang_df[col].value_counts()
            if lang_count.shape[0] > 0:
                year_data[region].append(lang_count.iloc[0])
            else:
                year_data[region].append(0)
    # now let's make a dataframe out of the data, update its labels and aggregate the regions
    year_data = pd.DataFrame(year_data)
    year_data.index = year_langs
    year_data = aggregate_regions(year_data)
    # now we can add it to the dictionary of language dataframes
    languages_per_region[year] = year_data

Observations:

  • Generally, all regions show similar usage of every language over time. No major differences stand out.
  • The top languages are web-based such as HTML, CSS and JavaScript, SQL which makes sense as most applications need a database and Java.
  • Percentage of participants using C, C++, C# and SQL compared to the total amount of participants is sinking globally.
  • Percentage of participants using JavaScript is also sinking globally. Simultaneously, the percentage of participants using JavaScript Frameworks such as NodeJS or AngularJS is rising globally.
  • Python usage is somewhat steady. It is higher in USA and Canada compared to the other regions, especially Asia which has the lowest % of participants using Python throughout all years.
  • Asia is the lowest in several languages such as Python, C#, SQL and even JavaScript and its frameworks across most years. In some languages like C# this difference is quite significant. They lead the usage counts in C.
  • The top languages on StackOverflow remain JavaScript, SQL and Java, with several JavaScript frameworks on the uprise.

The drop in the year 2017 is visible for nearly every language in every region. It is a reasonable assumption that this had other reasons than the popularity of the language dropping, such as survey design or targeting. As we cannot with certainty explain the reason behind the drop it may be better to look at the development from 2016 to 2018 as steady, thus ignoring the universal drop in 2017.

The sinking of participants using C, C++, C# and some of the other big languages may be due to the increase in language diversity on stackoverflow. It does not mean these languages actually get used less, but it may hint to stackoverflow increasing in popularity for people using other languages than the more common ones.

Programming as a hobby¶

For this question we only have to look at a single column: 'Programming_Hobby'. When preparing this column we already had to reshape it to only include the information: does the participant program as a hobby. Once again we cannot differentiate properly between "did not answer" and "answered no". We'll make the assumption that every participant that programs as a hobby answered the question with yes, everyone else either skipped the question (not answering it) or answered no.

Let's create a dataframe telling us how many people program as a hobby in each region and year. Then let's use the total amount of participants in each region and year to create relative values and plot them as we did before.

Company Size¶

Here, we can use the same procedure as we did for age and satisfaction. We'll create 4 dataframes, one for each of the size categories. As usual we'll create relative values and then plot them out.
